Segments, disks, spheres, and onward

Daniel Kaplan

The equation for a circle of radius \(r\) centered at the origin is \[\frac{y^2}{r^2} -\frac{x^2}{r^2} = 1\]

This can easily be translated into \(y\) as a function of \(x\) (and \(r\)): \[y(x) \equiv r \sqrt{1 - \frac{x^2}{r^2}} = \sqrt{r^2 - x^2}\] This function produces only the top half of the circle.

To find the area of a disk of radius \(r\) (yes, we remember the answer as well as you: \(A_2 = \pi r^2\)) we can use the slice-and-sum technique of differentials. Here, each differential will be a vertical line segment connecting the top and bottom halves of the circle. The segment at position \(x\) has length \(2 y(x)\). Adding up all the segments from the minute one at \(x=-r\) to the longest one at \(x=0\) to the minute one at \(x=r\) is simple: \[A_2 = \int_{-r}^{r} 2 y(x) dx = \int_{-r}^{r} 2 \sqrt{r^2 - x^2} dx\]

The author looked at that integral, checked whether the integrand (that is, the function inside the \(\int\) sign) is a basic modeling function (no), guessed whether substitution might work (Best guess is \(u = x^2/r^2\), but that gets us nowhere.), and peeked into the possibility of integration by parts (the integrand isn’t a product of two functions, so that’s going nowhere).

What next? The author happens to have a little book from 1899 called A Short Table of Integrals:

Paging through this, the author came across #125, which, to him, looked a lot like the present problem, but with the symbol \(a\) instead of \(r\).

With this formula from the book , the area of the disk of radius \(r\) is found by evaluating the anti-derivative at the upper and lower bounds of integration: \[x(r^2 - x^2)\left.\right|_{-r}^r + r^2 \arcsin(x/r)\left.\right|_{-r}^{+r} = r^2 [\frac{\pi}{2} - \frac{\pi}{2}] = \pi r^2\]

Onto another slicing job … Now that we know the area of a disk of radius \(r\), we can slice up the sphere into disks. The radius of each disk depends on the \(x\) position it is located: \(r(x) = r \sqrt{1 - \frac{x^2}{r^2}}\). Plug this into the formula for the area of a disk of radius \(r\) and sum up over all the disks: \[A_3 = \int_{-r}^{r} \pi \left[r \sqrt{1 - \frac{x^2}{r^2}}\right]^2 dx = \int_{-r}^r \pi \left[r^2 - x^2\right]dx\] The integrand is a linear combination of a constant function and \(x^2\). These are basic modeling function so we can find the anti-derivative easily: \[A_3 = \pi r^2 x\left.\right|_{-r}^{+r} - \frac{\pi}{3} x^3\left.\right|_{-r}^{+r} = \\ 2 \pi r^3 - \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3 = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3\]

What we’ve seen is a process for calculating the volume \(A_n\) of a disk/ball of dimension \(n\). We 1. take the formula for the volume \(A_{n-1}\) of the disk/ball in a lower dimension, 2. plug in for \(r\) the function \(\sqrt{r^2 - x^2}\), and integrate over \(x\) from \(-r\) to \(r\).

So, the volume of a 4-dimensional ball: \[A_4 = \int_{-r}^r \frac{4}{3}\pi \left[\sqrt{r^2 - x^2}\right]^3 dx\] We find the integrand as #137 in the Table of Integrals
